#summary It all started when you clicked that shiny "Use For Development" button in XCode.
#labels Reversing,Information,Featured

=Introduction=
(Thanks to AriX for helping research this)

If you attach an iPhone or iPod touch to your Mac, open Xcode, and click "Use For Development", an image gets uploaded onto your device. It is called "DeveloperDiskImage.dmg", and the DMG can be found here on your Mac:
{{{
/Developer/Platforms/iPhoneOS.platform/DiskImages/DeveloperDiskImage.dmg
}}}

It appears to contain iPhone (ARM) ports of the tools found in:
{{{
/Developer/Platforms/iPhoneOS.platform/Developer/SDKs/iPhoneOS2.0.sdk/Developer
}}}

You can check to see if it is mounted by SSHing into your device and typing 'mount':
{{{
iPwned-3G:/ root# mount
/dev/disk0s1 on / (hfs, local, noatime)
devfs on /dev (devfs, local)
/dev/disk0s2 on /private/var (hfs, local, noatime)
/dev/disk1 on /Developer (hfs, local, read-only) /* DeveloperDiskImage.dmg */
}}}

And if you don't believe that it is really the same Image as the one on your computer, run fsck on it:
{{{
iPwned-3G:/ root# fsck_hfs /dev/disk1
** /dev/rdisk1 (NO WRITE)
** Checking Non-journaled HFS Plus volume.
** Checking Extents Overflow file.
** Checking Catalog file.
** Checking multi-linked files.
** Checking Catalog hierarchy.
** Checking Extended Attributes file.
** Checking volume bitmap.
** Checking volume information.
** The volume DeveloperDiskImage appears to be OK.
}}}
=Mounting Procedure=
Pay attention when reading the iPhone part, as it can be a little bit confusing.
==From the XCode side==
XCode does the sending of the DeveloperDiskImage, as well as sending a plist file to the mobile_image_mounter daemon to communicate with it. At the time, the XCode side of things has not been reversed, so a detailed / verbose procedure cannot be provided as it is below.
==From the iPhone / iPod side==
1. Device receives plist of 'map'

2. Makes sure plist size is OK

3. Allocates memory according to the size of the plist

4. Creates a CFData object for it

5. Convert raw XML to plist

6. CFRelease the CFData in step 4

7. Free the memory that was malloc'd in step 3

8. Get value of the key "Command" from the sent plist

9. If it is not equal to "LookupImage", jump to step 18

=== If the "Command" value is equal to "LookupImage" ===

10. Get value of the key "ImageType" from the sent plist

11. Load Image Map

12. Create Mutable Dictionary (for response)

13. In the response dictionary, set key "ImagePresent" to value kCFBooleanFalse, and key "Status" to "Complete"

13b. Check if the value grabbed in 10. If it is not equal to NULL, then set up a dictionary with the following: "ImagePresent" set to kCFBooleanTrue, "ImageType" set to the value got in step 10, and "ImageDigest" set to what it was set to in the sent plist

14. Send response dictionary back to XCode

15. CFRelease the response dictionary

16. CFRelease the Image Map

17. Routine end

=== If the "Command" value is not equal to "LookupImage", a jump is made to this point ===

18. If the "Command value is not equal to "MountImage", jump to step 51

=== If the "Command" value is equal to "MountImage" ===

19. Get value of "ImageType" from sent plist

20. Get value of "ImageSignature" from sent plist

21. Get value of "ImagePath" from sent plist

22. If "ImageType" is "Developer" set a value to "/tmp/mobile_image_mounter/developer.dimage". If "ImageType" is "Developer", then set a value to "debug.dimage"

23. Create the directory "/tmp/mobile_image_mounter/" with permissions 755

24. Rename the directory created in step 23 with the value set in step 24

25. If "ImageType" is Developer, set a value to "/Developer". If "ImageType" is "Debug", then set a value to "/var/debug_mount/"

26. Use some 'fts' functions to assure that the directory defined in step 25 exist, that they can be read from, and that they are empty.

27. SHA1 hash the content of the path in step 22

28. Parse /System/Library/Lockdown/iPhoneDebug.pem

29. Create CFArray with certificate parsed in step 28

30. Create basic policy from array in created step 29

31. Create trust from policy created in step 30

32. Evaluate trust created in step 31

33. Copy public key from trust created in step 31

34. CFRelease trust created in step 31

35. CFRelease policy created in step 30

36. Get length of value returned from "ImageSignature" in step 20

37. Allocate memory for the length of the value retrieved in step 36

38. Verify public key

39. Free allocated memory

40. CFRelease the copied public key

41. CFRelease the parsed cert

42. Make the directory defined in step 25 with permissions 755

43. Create a response dictionary with some uninteresting info

44. Attach disk image

45. Find /dev node

46. Stat node

47. Store image map in /tmp/mobile_image_mounter/map.plist

48. If "ImageType" is "Developer", then post to notification center: com.apple.mobile.developer_image_mounted

49. Send response plist to XCode with key "Status" and value "Completed"

50. Done

=== If the "Command" value is equal to "Hangup" ===
51. This seems to not even be worth reversing. Thoughts?
